<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-876-022  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 876 022.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Oct 1989 v22 n10 p9(14).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Influence of visual technology on the evolution of languageenvironments. (Visualization in Computing) (includes relatedarticles on the use of various visual user interfaces) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ambler, Allen L.; Burnett, Margaret M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The use of visual technology in language environments has evolvedfrom the relatively straightforward translation of textualtechniques into equivalent visual techniques to the use of visualtechniques with no natural parallel in purely textual techniques.andO;The software support environments of the 1970s, such as Unix, andtheir programming environment subsets led to the development oflanguage environments that were tightly integrated around a singlelanguage.andP;  One of the first of these was Interlisp, which providedthe basic functionality of a language environment with its ownuser interface, editor, interpreter and symbolic debugger.andO;Smalltalk introduced the concept of multiple windows, and Pecanintroduced the use of multiple views, which share a commoninternal data representation of the same data.andP;  Among the othervisual language environments described are Cedar, Garden, theCornell Program Synthesizer, PegaSys, ThingLab, ThinkPad,Pictorial Transformations and Forms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Program Development TechniquesProgram Development ToolsVisualizationGraphical User InterfaceTechnologyNew TechniqueSoftware Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>